## Semantic Beacon System (SBS)

### What is SBS

The Semantic Beacon System is a network of inline tags embedded organically in your
project documentation. Each beacon is a cognitive navigation node that allows any LLM to:
- Identify the relative importance of each information fragment (weight W1-W5)
- Know the semantic domain without reading the full context (domain)
- Follow cross-layer connections without redundant reads (destination)
- Filter information by relevance to the current task (role)

### Canonical format

**Simple beacon:**
```
[*(DOMAIN.WEIGHT.ROLE>DESTINATION)*]
```

**Pack beacon (multiple dimensions):**
```
[*(DOMAIN.WEIGHT.ROLE>DESTINATION | DOMAIN.WEIGHT.ROLE>DESTINATION)*]
```

### Domains (semantic context)

Customize these for your project. The defaults below cover common scenarios:

| Code | Domain | Coverage |
|------|--------|----------|
| ARC | Architecture | Layers, patterns, system structure |
| SRV | Services | Docker, CI/CD, operational infrastructure |
| COG | Cognitive | Memory system, beacons, missions, protocols |
| HW | Hardware | Physical resources, monitoring |
| AI | AI Processes | Training, inference, models |
| EXT | External | Integrations, webhooks, APIs, cloud |
| SEC | Security | Auth, encryption, access control |
| BIZ | Business | Products, domains, strategy |
| UI | Interface | Dashboard, web, UX, templates |
| DAT | Data | Persistence, databases, caches |

### Weights (W1-W5 — LLM attention)

| Weight | Meaning | Implicit instruction |
|--------|---------|----------------------|
| W1 | Critical | ALWAYS read. Fundamental system definition |
| W2 | High | Read if the work context is relevant |
| W3 | Medium | Consult if deeper detail is needed |
| W4 | Low | Only if searching for specific detail |
| W5 | Note | Ignore unless directed search |

### Roles (semantic function)

| Code | Role | What it marks |
|------|------|---------------|
| DEF | Definition | What something IS — fundamental concept |
| DEC | Decision | Why something was chosen — architectural justification |
| DEP | Dependency | Requires or depends on another element |
| REF | Reference | See also — related content in another location |
| HIT | Milestone | Milestone reached or checkpoint |
| PAT | Pattern | Reusable pattern, exportable to other contexts |
| RIS | Risk | Identified threat or applied mitigation |
| EVL | Evolution | Change, progression, transformation of something prior |
| SIG | Signal | State transition of a process, mission, or trackable element |

### Destinations (where the beacon points)

| Format | Points to |
|--------|-----------|
| >MIS-XXX | Specific mission |
| >SN | Section N of MEMORY.md |
| >SR | SIGNAL_REGISTRY.md (general signal registry) |
| >SR.SIG-NNN | Specific signal in the registry |

### LLM usage protocol

1. **When reading a file**: Scan W1 beacons first — they are fundamental definitions
2. **When searching**: Filter by relevant domain (e.g., working on UI -> look for `[*(UI.*)*]`)
3. **When following references**: Beacons with ROLE=REF point to complementary content — follow only if needed
4. **When updating documents**: Insert beacons at semantically dense points (definitions, decisions, milestones)

